The known solution for this problem uses dynamic programming and a segment tree (or Fenwick tree) for optimization. Let:
  dp[i] = maximum total value we can achieve for the prefix ending at i (i.e., considering a[0..i-1] for 0-indexed array) We have:
  dp[0] = 0
  For i from 1 to n:
      dp[i] = max_{0<=j<i} { dp[j] + sign(S) * (i - j) } 
        where S = prefix[i] - prefix[j] (the sum of subarray from j to i-1) But note: the value for the segment [j, i-1] is:
        if S>0: then value = (i - j) -> so dp[j] + (i - j)
        if S=0: then value = 0 -> so dp[j] + 0
        if S<0: then value = -(i - j) -> so dp[j] - (i - j)

We can rewrite:
  dp[i] = max( 
        max_{j: prefix[i] - prefix[j] > 0} { dp[j] + (i - j) },
        max_{j: prefix[i] - prefix[j] = 0} { dp[j] },
        max_{j: prefix[i] - prefix[j] < 0} { dp[j] - (i - j) }
  ) Alternatively, we can express:
  dp[i] = max( 
        i + max_{j: prefix[j] < prefix[i]} { dp[j] - j },
        max_{j: prefix[j] = prefix[i]} { dp[j] },
        -i + max_{j: prefix[j] > prefix[i]} { dp[j] + j }
  )

But note: we must consider j from 0 to i.

